                {
                    "name": "Wild Gibtases",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "In the wild, gibtases are scavenger creatures, avoiding much larger and more powerful predators while feeding off abandoned scraps. This limits their consumption-based reproduction. By spawning hundreds of offspring at once during times of plentiful food, they ensure the propagation of their species only during times of plenty. ",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Pathfinder #164: Hands of the Devil",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Pathfinder #164: Hands of the Devil pg. 80",
                                "alt": "Pathfinder #164: Hands of the Devil pg. 80",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq024ur"
                            },
                            "page": 80
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    }
                }
            ],
            "text": "This rubbery, spheroid scavenger is nearly all acid-dripping mouth, with five bulbous black eyes and two powerful, gangly legs. A gibtas often forms a bond with a single other creature\u2014usually, a more powerful aberration\u2014 and serves this master loyally, if erratically. Creatures who keep a gibtas as a pet or guard soon learn to keep it away from any important possessions they don't want spattered with acid.",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #164: Hands of the Devil",
